		<title>Comment on Homework 4: Curvature Flow by Keenan Crane</title>
		<link>http://brickisland.net/cs177fa12/?p=320#comment-67</link>
		<dc:creator>Keenan Crane</dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Fri, 14 Dec 2012 23:16:37 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://brickisland.net/cs177fa12/?p=320#comment-67</guid>
		<description>You make a great point, Kevin.  The function \(&#124;\varphi&#124;\) isn&#039;t differentiable at zero, so it&#039;s no surprise that the gradient of the signed angle is ill-defined when \(u\) and \(v\) are parallel!

If, as you suggest, you use the signed angle then things behave better -- in this case, the gradient is something like
\[ \nabla_u \varphi = \frac{u^\perp}{&#124;u^\perp&#124;^2} \]
where \(u^\perp\) means \(u\) rotated a quarter-turn in the counter-clockwise direction.

For the assignment, you can get things to work by simply checking whether \(A\) is close to zero.  But I&#039;ll be sure to incorporate this observation into future versions of the assignment.</description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>You make a great point, Kevin.  The function \(|\varphi|\) isn&#8217;t differentiable at zero, so it&#8217;s no surprise that the gradient of the signed angle is ill-defined when \(u\) and \(v\) are parallel!</p>
<p>If, as you suggest, you use the signed angle then things behave better &#8212; in this case, the gradient is something like<br />
\[ \nabla_u \varphi = \frac{u^\perp}{|u^\perp|^2} \]<br />
where \(u^\perp\) means \(u\) rotated a quarter-turn in the counter-clockwise direction.</p>
<p>For the assignment, you can get things to work by simply checking whether \(A\) is close to zero.  But I&#8217;ll be sure to incorporate this observation into future versions of the assignment.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
